etymologies: mid 16th century; earliest use found in Richard Eden (c1520–1576), translator. From sub- + celestial

definitions: Existing below or beneath a heavenly or ethereal realm; material (as opposed to ethereal).

notes.text: Frequently in relation to cosmological or theological hierarchies.

definitions: In weakened sense: earthly, mundane, inferior. Compare "sublunary". Now rare (chiefly archaic and poetic).
Situated or occurring beneath the celestial sphere, specifically on the earth directly beneath the zenith.
A subcelestial entity or being. Also (with the): such beings collectively.
